					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">There is an alternative approach, where you literally just give the converter a 256x240 pixel PNG image plus a 32-character hex string representing the NES palette that you want to use. However, it requires installation of a Python interpreter as well as use of the command prompt.* This &quot;savtool&quot;, as I call it, is bundled with my <a href="https://pineight.com/nes/#editor" class="postlink">graphics editor for NES</a>.<br /><br />Or do you require that it be point and click and in the form of a single EXE for the Microsoft Windows operating system? If so, let me know, and I may put it on my list of things to make for the community once <em>The Curse of Possum Hollow</em> wraps.<br /><br /><br /><span style="font-size: 85%; line-height: normal">* I prefer the command line for data conversion tools like these because it allows me to script the conversion in a makefile, so that when I edit the original PNG image, Make can detect the changes and re-run the conversion.</span></div>

